post_text: Superintendent Irish met with new United Way of Skagit County Executive Director Craig Chambers today. They discussed ways that the district can partner with United Way, especially as they continue to focus on their early learning campaign, by ensuring that every 5 year old is ready to learn by 2025. Justin and Craig also discussed how United Way and the school district are continuing their equity work to break the cycle of poverty and combat institutional racism.

With changes occurring almost daily, families have many questions about what school will look like in the fall. Here's a closer look at the district's learning options. Finance Director Dave Cram explains just how important enrollment is for district funding, and Assistant Superintendent Dr. Becky Clifford gives a detailed description of both learning models, so families can make the choice that works best for them.

There will also be two informational sessions hosted by Director of Teaching and Learning Angie Miller and Assistant Superintendent Dr. Becky Clifford on Wednesday August 12th at 5:30 and again Friday August 14th at 12:00. For links to the info sessions, please check the district's website: www.asd103.org

Selection will open on Monday, August 17. Families will be sent a survey to fill out on that day.

https://youtu.be/gHl3KCfdnVk

post_text:
Join us in recognizing Juneteenth - the oldest nationally celebrated commemoration of the ending of slavery in the United States, memorializing the day that news of the Civil War's ending reached Galveston, Texas, and 250,000 enslaved Texans found out that they had been free for over two years. 155 years later, we clearly have much more work to do to combat racism, bias, and hate.

The Anacortes School District is committed to doing the hard work: to educate, to learn, to listen, and to act.

We invite you to join us in learning more.

Please check out the following resources:
https://www.tolerance.org/

https://mlpp.org/21-day-racial-equity-challenge/

https://nmaahc.si.edu/learn/talking-about-race/topics/being-antiracist?blm_aid=9240577

https://www.facebook.com/watch/?v=3392928634109391

post_text: Last week, district staff distributed new books to about 375 students, following the buses delivering lunches each day. The books were purchased through Scholastic Book Fair credits from previous book fairs, held at each of the elementary schools. The mystery book bags were labeled by grade-level and handed out to students at each stop. Kids ranging from 4 to 18 received books to continue their summer reading. The bags also included information on the Anacortes Public Library Summer reading program, bookmarks, and book title tattoos and stickers that were generously donated by Scholastic Book Fairs. Happy reading everyone!

The bags also included information on the Anacortes Public Library Summer reading program, bookmarks, and book title tattoos and stickers that were generously donated by Scholastic Book Fairs. Happy reading everyone!

post_text:
“My job is as exhausting as it is energizing. And I love this dichotomy.” Julie Riccardi has taught kindergarten for 14 years, one of those as a K-2 literacy coach, and she says she learns so much from her students about kindness and curiosity. Creating lessons that are engaging for students and seeing them take ownership of their learning while developing confidence is a huge reward.

Her passion for literacy has helped her lead the efforts to move to online learning during the school closure; district kindergarten teachers are using Seesaw to connect with students via video lessons, student-to-student posts, and multi-media interactive lessons. Students (and parents) can then respond in a variety of ways as well.

Riccardi is grateful to have a job that impacts the future and matters in society; at the same time, she takes that responsibility very seriously. And we are grateful that she is making that impact here in Anacortes. Thank you, Mrs. Riccardi.

post_text:
“I am so thankful to be teaching in this district. The students are great, the parents are great, and the district support is great. I’m proud of how thoughtful and intentional district staff and families have been; it has really been felt during this time of crises," says Luke Stanage.

Stanage has taught 4th grade at Mt. Erie for seven years and loves that his job is creative and that no two days are ever the same. Finding the sweet spot in teaching when students are self-motivated about learning and also growing deeply in their character is what he loves most.

He is also proud of how much ingenuity and creativity his students are showing through their school closure journals, writing non-fiction, sharing photos of high level math work and writing nature poems or fiction stories.

Thank you for encouraging and inspiring your students every day, Mr. Stanage.

post_text:
For nearly 30 years, Amy Ubungen has taught a variety of subjects at every grade level, the last 16 of those here in Anacortes. She has taught Spanish at AMS and AHS and has been a class advisor and AVID instructor at the high school. And her entire teaching career has been about relationships.

“I love students’ optimism, their creativity and their resilience. I love the hope that students have, that even when things are not going as planned, they are still malleable enough to be encouraged and inspired. They inspire me to keep going.”

Ubungen says connecting with students is easy when you care about them. “Their perception is their reality, so acknowledging that their feelings are important is key. I also believe that kindness matters.”

Next year, Ubungen will be sharing her passion for student success as the director of the WA World Fellows program, a program that selects sophomores from around the state and provides them with opportunities to be successful in high school and college.

Thank you for your dedication to Anacortes students and best of luck in your future endeavors!

post_text:
Join us in celebrating Teacher Appreciation Week (May 4-8) and School Nurse Appreciation Day (May 6)!

Now, more than ever, we have seen our teachers rise to new challenges, embrace change, and continue providing high-quality education in our distance-learning model.

We will be highlighting some of our staff here throughout the week.

Superintendent Mark Wenzel expressed appreciation for our teachers and noted the creativity he has seen throughout the pandemic.

“I am so proud of our teachers. I have seen them come together to support one another in very challenging times,” said Wenzel. “They are teaching from home, caring for families as well, and adapting to our new learning model.”

Wenzel also expressed appreciation for the district’s nurses, who have been helping to staff the district’s child care program.

“Our nurses are incredibly dedicated, organized, and have a heart for children,” said Wenzel. “I’m grateful to them for their help in making sure that we can run our childcare program safely.”

post_text:
For three decades, Anka Kolega has been keeping our students nourished. This is her 27th year in food service, but before that she subbed and even before that she was a volunteer for years while her two sons were in elementary school.

Kolega has called Anacortes home for 46 years, although she was born in Croatia and continues to visit there each summer. When she's not working, she enjoys gardening, and singing, her number one passion.

She absolutely loves her job. "I call them my kids. And they are, Every one. In 27 years, I have not had a student be disrespectful to me. They know I care about them, and they come back after graduation to tell me they remember me."

Thank you, Anka, for you decades of service and for sharing your positivity with our students!

Sage Petrin is a globe trotter. Literally. From France and Italy to Mozambique and Cambodia, she has circled the globe. The middle school paraeducator, now in her third year, says she's glad she traveled when she was younger before she had a family. Raised in Anacortes since the age of two, Petrin's first job was at Calico Cupboard when she was 14. She still has customers who remember her.

Petrin now works in the AMS resource room and say her favorite part of the job is when a student finally gets "it". When they reach a goal they've been working hard to attain.

"That moment is so special, and it can carry me through a week or more. I just love seeing their pride at accomplishing a goal."

Thank you Sage!

Born and raised in Anacortes, electrical maintenance worker Lance Henning says his is a perfect job for him.

"I love working with my hands. Every day is different. Sometimes I"m checking heating controls; some days I'm replacing electronic controllers for hot water valves."

Henning, who has been with the district for three years, can actually control the heating and lighting in all the buildings from his office at the maintenance building. When he's not working, he enjoys spending time with his wife and dog. He is also a photographer and a certified drone pilot who recently shot a wedding in Costa Rica. Thanks, Lance, for working hard to make us all comfortable and to keep things running smoothly.

Colleagues and students know her by her love of music. "It's my thing," says middle school head custodian Doreen Rogers. She loves to listen to the blues, and she LOVES to dance. She plays a mean harmonica, to boot. Her Irish born parents might have something to do with her connection to all things musical.

Rogers moved from New York to Washington State in 1996 and has been with the district for six years. She has always worked in school districts, whether it be food service or custodial work, although she does own her own cleaning business as well.

She considers herself lucky to have such great staff to work with and such helpful students. Thank you, Doreen, for keeping our schools in tip top shape. Keep on playing and dancing!

When he's not tending to the district's infrastructure, Naun Gallardo prefers to spend his time with family and friends or listening to music, rock and disco to be specific. Originally from Ecuador, Gallardo lived in New York then California before moving to Anacortes. He worked at Sun Systems for five years then made the move to the district, where he has been a district network engineer for 18 years and thoroughly enjoys his job.

"I love it because everything is a challenge. I'm helping students and staff and even the community when I solve the daily problems,"

Gallardo notes that most of his job is unseen, so people often don't know what it is that he does. If you see him around, be sure to thank him for his behind-the-scenes magic.

March is I Love to Read month, which is perfect for Mt. Erie office manager Melissa Reeder as reading is her number one hobby. A second love is Baby Yoda. While Reeder has only been in the position for a few months, she has worked in the district for five years. And if you think you're seeing double when you go to Mt. Erie or Anacortes High School, you're not crazy. Reeder and AHS front secretary Kellie Franklin are sisters.

Originally from Utah, Reeder has lived in Washington for 15 years. She graduated as a Communications major from Western Washington University. Reeder and her husband have two kids (6th and 9th grade) and two really cute dogs.

"I love my job because we have the BEST staff ever," she says. Thank you for your hard work and your welcoming smile, Mrs. Reeder!

Nominations are now being accepted for the Walter A. Brodniak Award for Cultural Education.

The Brodniak Award was created to foster growth of the cultural arts in the school district. Brodniak, Anacortes School District Superintendent from 1973 to 1977, was a staunch believer in the powerful contributions that arts make to our community. Each year, the award is given to a student, faculty member, administrator, school director, community member or organization that has made an outstanding contribution to the cultural arts in the Anacortes School District in the past year.

Nominations are due by 5 p.m. Friday, April 17, 2020. Please use the online form (www.asd103.org) to submit your nomination. A selection committee will review the nominations and make a recommendation to the School Board. The recipient will be recognized at a special community reception in May.
http://www.asd103.org/news/what_s_new/nominations_open_for_brodniak_arts_award

If you have questions, please contact the Superintendent’s Office at (360) 503-1211 or tramsay@asd103.org.

This morning, White Hatter Darren Laur engaged middle and high school students in an age-appropriate presentation that addressed all aspects of internet safety and digital literacy. He showed the legal, emotional, psychological, physical, social and technical benefits and ramifications of using social media both responsibly and irresponsibly.

Using humor and real-life examples, Laur encouraged students to think before they post. He also underscored the notion that cyber bullying, or digital peer aggression, is an act of violence, not harmless teasing.

Parents are encouraged to attend tonight's event at 6:30 in Brodniak. Laur will sum up this morning's talk and speak frankly to parents about what they can do to help protect their students.

post_text:
We will hold our annual health screenings at schools throughout Feb 3-6. Your student will be screened for hearing and vision. If your student does not receive passing results on either screen, you will be contacted by the school nurse with individual results.

The schedule for the health screenings is as follows:

Monday, February 3rd: Fidalgo 9-2 p.m.

Tuesday, February 4th: Mount Erie 9-2 p.m.

Wednesday, February 5th: AMS 8-11 a.m. and Whitney 12-2:30 p.m.

Thursday, February 6th: Island View 9:05 a.m. - 2:30 p.m.

Please note: This screening does not replace a professional examination. Although school based screenings can indicate many abnormalities, it is not an all-inclusive screen. If you have hearing or vision concerns for your child please contact their primary care provider for further examination.

Questions? Contact Nurse Emily Wade: 360-503-1552 or ewade@asd103.org

Thank you for your patience this week with our wild winter weather. Below are calendar changes based on this week's impacts.

a) To accommodate the end of the semester and grading, we will shift the half day from Friday January 24 to Friday January 31. The 24th (next Friday) is now a full day for students; the 31st is a half day.

To make up the three days of school, we will:

b) Move the last day of school to June 19 from June 18

b) Make the March 13 staff learning day a school day and moving the PD day to Monday June 22 (leaves apply)

c) Use the snow day on May 22 as a regular school day

The updated calendar is posted on our website: http://www.asd103.org/

post_text: Palestinian-born Asil Jabr, a refugee herself, spent time in three Island View classrooms last week, sharing her art and her story of living in Jordan. Students across Skagit Valley are working with her on art and poetry through Voices of the Children. Their "Legacy" art will be shared with Syrian refugee students in Amman, Jordan. Likewise, poems and art from the refugee school, where Jabr directs Voices of the Children, will be sent to schools in Skagit Valley.

post_text:
"I think the world needs problem solvers, and that's why I love teaching math," says middle school math teacher Holly Besmer. New to ASD this year, Besmer taught math for eight years in the Mukilteo school district.

In both her 7th grade math and her Algebra 1 classes, Besmer focuses on math practices such as critical thinking, reasoning and modeling. She continually encourages curiosity and creates activities that incorporate multiple styles of learning. Students compare different strategies of approaching problems and learn to explain their thinking.

"I try to open my classroom to all types of learners. Our goal is to notice and wonder, and any student who claims she doesn't get it, will hear me say, "You don't get it....yet.' That's the growth mindset with which we're working."

She continually encourages curiosity and creates activities that incorporate multiple styles of learning. "I try to open my classroom to all types of learners. Our goal is to notice and wonder, and any student who claims she doesn't get it, will hear me say, "You don't get it....yet.' That's the growth mindset with which we're working."

post_text:
We invite the community to visit Veterans Memorial Plaza at Anacortes High School this Veterans Day and show appreciation to all the brave men and women who have served, and continue to serve, our country.

The plaza will be open to the public from 10 a.m. to noon on Monday, November 11. No events are planned; rather we invite the community in for reflection and tribute. Restrooms will be open during this time. The plaza is comprised of a memorial designed by local architect Brooks Middleton, with input from the Veterans Memorial Committee, as well as a display honoring two Medal of Honor recipients with local connections. The Anacortes School District is closed on Monday, November 11.

Questions, please contact the Superintendent’s Office at (360) 503-1211 or tramsay@asd103.org.

post_text:
In partnership with Anacortes Public Library and NASA@ My Library, we are proud to host Captain Heidemarie Stefanyshyn-Piper at Anacortes High School at 7 p.m. on Wednesday, Oct. 30.

Stefanyshyn-Piper has received numerous honors and awards, such as the Meritorious Service Medal, two Navy Commendation Medals, and two Navy Achievement Medals. She has flown on two Space Shuttle missions, STS-115 and STS-126, during which she completed five spacewalks totaling 33 hours and 42 minutes. As of 2019, she ranks 39th on the all-time list of space walkers by duration.

This event is free and open to the public.

post_text:
Congratulations to Anacortes Middle School ELA teachers and students for scoring the highest out of 35 school districts in our region on the Washington State OSPI report card. Seventh grade teacher Kristen Chambers says it's a team effort.

"It's not just us. We have great technology in our hands and wonderful tech support. We have literacy coaches who help us, too. It all adds up.These students have been doing our Writers' Workshop curriculum since second and third grade, and it's paying off now. They have a solid foundation, and we just get to do the magic. The workshop model is special because it allows us to look at the progression of each student. And we know students learn so differently, so seeing their individual growth is a powerful element of teaching. I check in weekly with my students by asking them to write one thing they want me to know that week. This gives me a way into conversations with them. They can only become better writers if they feel heard and seen, and I need to get to know them in order for that to transpire."

Meet April Lyons-Dixon, new life skills teacher at Anacortes High School!

Ms. Lyons-Dixon comes to us most recently from Colorado and before that Wyoming. Her entry into teaching Special Education came via substitute teaching, where she fell in love with it. And she is still loving it as her class this year is full of “enthusiastic great kids. They are always excited about learning new things. I just love their sense of wonder.”

Lyons-Dixon has twin boys in elementary school that keep her quite busy, but she does find time to travel, camp and whitewater raft with her family during the summer. In fact, she has been to every state except Hawaii. As a new parent in the district, she has been most impressed with the emphasis on the whole student, that kids are looked at for who they are, not solely their test scores. Welcome, Ms. Lyons-Dixon.

Monica Harris is finally back in the classroom as a special education teacher, the role she held more than fifteen years ago before her children were born. Originally from Maryland, Harris has lived in Anacortes a few times due to her husband’s military career. For the past couple of years, she has worked as a para educator at Whitney, but when this position opened, she decided to return to her roots in special education. Her job allows her to be in all four kindergarten classes, which is one of the benefits of teaching at Whitney. Another is that all three of her own children attended, so it’s near to her heart.

The most rewarding part of her job is when students realize their tiny successes. At this age, even the small things, such as following tasks, are cause for celebration. Having three sons at different schools keeps Harris quite busy. She enjoys attending their various sporting events and running with her husband. Welcome back to the classroom, Mrs. Harris!

post_text:
Meet Marielle Face -- new resource room teacher at Island View.

In her first ever teaching job, Ms. Face is settling in and enjoying her students very much. A graduate of Western Washington University, she earned a dual endorsement in elementary and special education. While she always knew she wanted to be a teacher, it wasn’t until she actually started taking some of the special education classes that her love for the discipline was cemented. Growing up in Issaquah, Face and her family were very involved in Bridging Disabilities Ministry. "I’ve been around people with various ability levels most of my life," she says.

What brings Face the greatest joy is when her students “get” something they’ve been working so hard to understand. “To see them finally make a connection after struggling with it is the best. I just love their excitement and pride.”

If it has anything to do with mountains, the forest or water, Face will be there. She loves hiking, climbing and skiing and can be found outside more often than not when she’s not in the classroom. Welcome to the district, Ms. Face!

post_text:
Meet Joanna Thayne - movement specialist at Island View.

“Working here feels like coming home. It’s such a welcoming school and district.” Mrs. Thayne is not necessarily new to the district in the strictest of terms. She has subbed K-12 since she moved here three years ago. But she is very excited to now be teaching full-time in the district that “blew her out of the water.”

Thayne had homeschooled her son when they lived in California because he just wasn’t succeeding in their district. After enrolling him part-time in ASD, she was so impressed with his progress and attitude, that she enrolled him full time.
Her position is a natural fit as she believes wholeheartedly that we all need movement and play to better learn. Her goal is to connect with her students and make sure that all of them feel seen and heard. Welcome home, Mrs. Thayne.

post_text:
Since preschool, Amy Kammenga has known she wanted to be a teacher. And her desire to work in special education came shortly after in elementary school. She saw classmates with disabilities being treated differently, and she didn’t think that was fair. Kammenga started working with Life Skills kids during her high school years at Mt. Vernon High School; in fact, she started a program called The Unity Project and coached the Special Olympics Unified soccer team.

Kammenga says she loves figuring out how to support her kids because they are all so capable of fantastic things when they have support.

“I love my students’ honesty and passion, and I love harnessing that passion to motivate them. Being able to look back and see their progress is huge. Sometimes the growth takes a long time, but it’s worth it. We celebrate all the little victories, and they are so proud.” Welcome to the district, Ms. Kammenga.

post_text:
We are continuing our introduction of new staff with Carter O'Donnell, who is teaching kindergarten at Whitney.

Ten days before Carter O’Donnell and her family were set to move to the Middle East, they got the orders to come to Anacortes. That was seven years ago, and they’re here to stay. O’Donnell returns to the classroom after staying home with her four children: 8th grade, 6th grade, 3rd grade and kindergarten. As they’ve grown, she realized she missed being in the classroom. She says the district’s reading and writing curriculum made such a huge difference for two of her children that she eagerly made the transition from Montessori teacher (15 years) to public school teacher. Her environmental science background has taken her to New Zealand where she studied conservation to the top of Mt. Kilamanjaro. What does she love about teaching kindergarten? “They are so eager and excited about everything. You’re always their superhero. It’s a privilege to be the first teacher of their public education.”

Welcome to the district, Mrs. O’Donnell!

A new school year brings new staff to our team! We will be introducing you to a few over the next few days.

First up, meet Josh Emery -- health and personal finance teacher at Anacortes High School.

When Josh Emery isn’t in the classroom, he can most likely be found outside, either climbing or on the trails. He loves both rock and alpine climbing and ultramarathon running. Emery comes to Anacortes most recently from Tonasket but has taught in Alaska and Seattle as well. This is his seventh year teaching, and he’s looking forward to making connections with his students. He has been impressed with the high expectations of the district and is confident that he’ll be teaching at a much higher level than in previous schools. Emery lives in a tiny house with his partner and two dogs and also enjoys woodworking. Welcome to Anacortes, Mr. Emery.

post_text:
Anacortes Schools start on Thursday, September 5, and we urge drivers to slow down and watch for pedestrians, especially in school zones. School zones can be particularly busy, especially before and after school. Drivers are reminded to share the road with pedestrians, school buses, and bicyclists. The speed limit in school zones is 20 MPH.

The district also has new start times at several schools this year.

The area around the high school remains a construction site as we continue phase III of the project – remodeling of Brodniak Hall and the gym, and construction of a new Cap Sante High School, career and technical education, drama and music classrooms. Please be mindful of construction vehicles and changing road conditions as we work to finish the project.

The National Safety Council (www.nsc.org) offers a number of good tips for drivers, cyclists, and pedestrians. We urge everyone out there to be safe and follow the rules of the road.

Following the successful ratification of our teachers’ contract, there are some changes to the Anacortes School District 2019-20 student and staff calendars.

New calendars are posted on the district’s website: www.asd103.org

The changes are:

Oct. 31 - K-5 half day for elementary students and staff

Dec. 20 - K-5 half day for elementary students and staff

Jan. 24 - K-12 half day for all students and elementary staff

April 16 - K-12 half day for all students and elementary staff

The student art calendars that were mailed last week do not reflect these changes due to our print deadlines and the negotiations schedule. All online calendars are up to date. The first day of school remains Thursday, Sept 5 and the last day remains Thursday, June 18.

Questions? Contact the Superintendent's Office - 360-503-1211 or tramsay@asd103.org

Elementary building placements were emailed to families on the morning of Friday, August 16.

Classroom placements will be emailed to families on Monday, August 26.

If you would like to appeal your building placement, please submit an appeal form to our Teaching and Learning Department via this link: https://forms.gle/UCgGFjAdzvMmNQz26. Per district policy (3131), appeals must be submitted in writing.

Principals meet regularly to review appeals and make decisions based on class size, gender balance, and other district-approved guidelines. Classroom placement appeals must be submitted to your principal.

If you didn’t receive a placement email or you have other questions, please contact our Teaching & Learning Department Program Assistant Wendy Durham, (360) 503-1212 or wdurham@asd103.org.

post_text:
Due to low interest among high school upperclass students, and out of a concern for student safety, Anacortes won’t field a varsity football team in the fall.

“We are disappointed that we won’t have a viable varsity team next year,” said Erik Titus, Anacortes athletics and activities director. “But it doesn’t make sense in terms of student health and safety to push inexperienced sophomores or freshman into varsity play before they are ready.”

The district will offer seniors with previous varsity-level experience an opportunity to play with another Skagit County school through an inter-cooperative agreement.

“We will continue to build our program and take full advantage of our new stadium,” said Titus. “We remain committed to offering a football program that balances student safety and competition.”

Titus plans to work with other districts to develop a junior varsity-level schedule for the season, including Homecoming.

Questions? Contact Erik Titus, Athletics and Activities Director, (360) 503-1305 or etitus@asd103.org
